257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 172 "Factor each polynomial and determine whether
 Maple was able to find enough linear factors to demonstrate the above
 assertion about the appropriate number of linear factors." }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did not find enough linear \+
factors, there is a reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumpti
on that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as \+
integers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only i
nterested in finding exact factors (factors where the coefficients are
 integers or rational numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra do
esn't guarantee that the factors of  a polynomial will necessarily hav
e the same kind of coefficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial
 can be factored.  You can force Maple to report additional (approxima
te) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}
