{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A relate
d theorem about finding roots of polynomials (equivalently factoring p
olynomials into a product of linear factors) asserts that if the polyn
omial has real coefficients -- all of the polynomials we have consider
ed (and will consider) have had real coefficients -- then any complex \+
roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For example, both t
he complex factors of " }{TEXT 282 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }
{TEXT 283 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pair
s.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new polynomials, name t
hem F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any \+
complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 
258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 136 "F1:= 35*x^5+16*x^4+9*x^3+4*x^2+2*x+1,  G1:=1
2*x^6+ 3*x^5+20*x^4+15*x^3+12*x^2+7*x+5, H1:=49*x^7+25*x^6+40*x^5+28*x
^4+30*x^3+14*x^2+3*x+7" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 59 "F1
:= 35*x^5+16*x^4+9*x^3+4*x^2+2*x+1;\nfactor (F1, complex);" }}{PARA 
